thinking:
We need to evaluate the described visualization for misleading aspects.

Description: line chart with weekly cases actual vs expected (projection). Both lines are red (solid vs dashed). Y-axis 0 to 900? Wait expected line rises to 4,127 cases by March 2021, but y-axis only up to 900. That suggests truncation: the expected line goes beyond axis limit, maybe not visible, but description says continues to rise to around 4,127 cases. If y-axis max is 900, then expected line cannot be shown correctly; maybe they used a secondary axis? Not mentioned. Could be that expected line is plotted on same axis but axis is truncated (max 900) making expected line appear far above chart, perhaps out of view. This is a serious distortion: they claim expected cases are 4,127 but chart y-axis only 0-900, so either axis is truncated (max cut) or they used a different scaling (dual axis). Since they didn't mention second axis, likely they truncated the y-axis, showing only up to 900, which underrepresents expected cases, making divergence look smaller? Actually they say divergence after lockdown continues to rise to around 4,127 but y-axis max 900. So maybe they used a second axis but not indicated. This is misleading.

Also cherry-picking: only showing period Nov 2020 to March 2021, maybe not showing later resurgence. But we can't assume.

Potential error: Setting an arbitrary threshold? Not exactly.

Causal inference: claim lockdown caused reduction, based on divergence of lines. That's causal inference from visual correlation, maybe unwarranted without control.

Incorrect reading: they estimate 22% reduction by comparing peaks (800 vs 1025). But expected peak is 1025? Yet they said expected line continues to rise to 4127 after March, but peak earlier? In any case, they use visual estimate, but might be incorrect reading.

Truncated axis is definite error. Also causal inference. Possibly cherry-picking if only showing data that supports claim.

Now evaluate intention: Likely intentional to make lockdown look effective; but could be unintentional due to poor design. I'd assign moderate confidence that it's intentional, say 65%.

Rhetoric types:

Information Access Rhetoric: Yes, they choose to include only weekly actual vs expected and limited time range; exists. Supports misleading (by omitting later data, maybe). Confidence 80.

Provenance Rhetoric: Not mentioned sources, methods for expected cases. So likely absent. Confidence 70.

Mapping Rhetoric: Mapping of values to position; use of red color both lines may cause confusion, but mapping is standard line chart. However use of same color might mislead; still mapping decisions matter. Exists. Confidence 75. Does it support misleading? Yes, because same color makes it harder to differentiate, possibly bias. So true.

Linguistic-Based Rhetoric: Title, annotation, caption with "Lockdown did probably reduce the number of cases by up to 22% though..." This frames interpretation, causal claim. So exists. Confidence 90. Supports misleading yes.

Procedural Rhetoric: No interaction described. Likely not present. Confidence 80 false.
